ke, Poudyal gravitated toward Nepal's oddballs and outcasts.</br>3) Many of these visitors are the outcasts of the Ghani government, men who have been fired, embarrassed, ignored or betrayed.</br>4) Her continuous interest and distinctive style in documenting America’s youth has taken her across the country to focus on promgoers, football stars and urban outcasts.</br>5) The original film, which came out in 1996, starred Robin Tunney as the newest member of a group of school outcasts.</br>\"\ntheorized,\"1) v construct a theory about</br>2) v form or construct theories</br>3) v to believe especially on uncertain or tentative grounds</br></br>  1) They theorized that Facebook could let users incorporate their doppelgangers into its service.</br>2) He theorized that higher concentrations of former prisoners in the old neighborhoods might have something to do with the difference.</br>3) It may be that both problems have similar genetic causes or share the same risk factors, the researchers theorized.</br>4) He theorized that there might be a problem with the hotel’s server.</br>5) He theorized that the black tape he wrapped around the wrist after falling pushed the pain to the top of his hand.</br>\"\ncentury,\"1) n a period of 100 years</br>2) n ten 10s</br></br>100 years is called a century. The computer, the television, and video games were all invented in the twentieth century. People are now wondering what the twenty-first century holds for us.</br></br> The noun century comes from the Latin word centuria, which was a group of 100, particularly a group of 100 Roman soldiers (one of 16 such groups in a Roman legion). The word today still can refer to 100 of something. In sports, a century is a score of 100 in a game of cricket. A race of 100 yards or 100 miles is also sometimes called a century. In slang, century can also mean a 100 dollar bill.</br></br> 1) This Venezuelan revolution is the music story thus far of the 21st century.</br>2) Almost three-quarters of 