es explicitly recognize this list as the benchmark for integrated care.</br>5) Hollywood complains that bootleg copies of their movies are rampant in some of the countries involved in the proposed partnership.</br>\"\nabstruse,\"1) adj difficult to penetrate; incomprehensible to one of ordinary understanding or knowledge</br></br>Abstruse things are difficult to understand because they are so deep and intellectually challenging. It might be hard to figure out how a toilet flushes but the technology that goes into making the Internet function is abstruse.</br></br> The Latin roots of the word abstruse are about concealing or hiding something, which is a good way to remember the meaning of this word. It is useful when describing something that is overly confusing, or if someone is deliberately making a story or a situation more complicated than necessary. It sounds and looks like obtuse, but abstruse is almost its opposite. Obtuse is dull or lacking a sharpness of intellect. While Abstruse is president of the chess club, Obtuse is hanging out by the parking lot smoking cigarettes.</br></br> 1) No, I don’t mean economics, or the abstruse arguments about whether we should use monetary or fiscal policy.</br>2) Mr. Gervasoni unites 13 abstruse couplets with a single tone row.</br>3) Pontecorvo’s seminal work on the subatomic particles called neutrinos is particularly abstruse.</br>4) His analysis is credible but, as the writers and producers told him, way too abstruse for anyone in the audience to think about.</br>5) But this somewhat abstruse, semantic argument risks concealing the issues at stake - should religion be afforded special legislative or even constitutional protection?</br>\"\nenigma,\"1) n something that baffles understanding and cannot be explained</br>2) n a difficult problem</br></br>Take the noun, enigma, for something that is a puzzle or a mystery. Why do you have to learn difficult words like this? That is an enigma.</br></br> Traveling to English from