uises,\"\" someone complained recently on Twitter, asking, \"\"When does it cease to be deep tissue massage therapy and become egregious and unabashed manhandling?\"\" An egregious error is hardly forgivable. Some synonyms are shocking, appalling, and intolerable. The word has made a 180-degree turn from its original sense in Latin, when it meant \"\"exceptionally good.\"\" Word historians have speculated that the negative usage was originally meant to be ironic, but it is the only sense that has survived. Be careful not to use it to mean \"\"outstanding,\"\" since no one wants to be called egregious.</br></br> 1) Our intrepid team of investigators has diagnosed the most egregious cheaters among us.</br>2) However, no individual has the right to an after-the-fact vengeance killing, no matter how egregious the original act.</br>3) He concludes, calling The Lego Movie an “especially egregious slam on business.”</br>4) Of all of Walmart’s egregious practices overtime, this is the one that’s probably the most well-known.</br>5) This is the only way to make this egregiously expensive healthcare system re-organize itself to  a lower cost base.</br>\"\nsubjection,\"1) n the act of conquering</br>2) n forced submission to control by others</br></br>Subjection is when a person, group, or government forces another person — or group of people — to submit or be controlled. A dictator's power lies in his subjection of the people over whom he rules.</br></br> Many kinds of control can be called subjection, but it most often describes a political rule or the subjugation of a large group of people. Slavery is one terrible, extreme type of subjection, and a king's conquering of a neighboring kingdom is another type. Subjection comes from the Old French subjection, \"\"submission, inferior condition, or captivity,\"\" with a Latin root, subjectionem, a putting under.\"\"</br></br> 1) The pair had escaped subjection in a newly independent Ukraine only to land in an American jail.</br>