ernational vanguard of successful music festivals.</br>4) I wonder if it will be the vanguard of a new type of more interactive programming.</br>5) Such a hybrid model was recently announced by the Vanguard Group, the large mutual fund company.</br>\"\nliteracy,\"1) n the ability to read and write</br></br>If you can read this sentence and write one of your own, you possess literacy.</br></br> In Latin, littera means \"\"letter.\"\" Back in the day, a person who could read and write was described as lettered. Literacy  can also mean having knowledge or ability in a more specific area. Since you bought grandma that laptop, her computer literacy has really improved: she just posted her newest exercise video.</br></br> 1) The more religious you are, the lower your scientific literacy.</br>2) Jimmy Patterson is the latest in a string of endeavors by the author to encourage infant literacy.</br>3) The event was hosted by the Duchess of Cornwall, who is a patron of the National Literacy Trust.</br>4) Members of an Assembly money committee voted unanimously to allocate $27.2 million to the governor’s “Read by 3” literacy initiative earlier in May.</br>5) He has dedicated part of his fortune to philanthropic projects aimed at increasing literacy and bolstering struggling independent booksellers.</br>\"\ninfamy,\"1) n a state of extreme dishonor</br>2) n evil fame or public reputation</br></br>Infamy means being famous for something bad or negative. You may be hoping for fame when you get an enormous tattoo of your favorite pop star on your back, but there's a chance you'll end up with infamy instead.</br></br> The noun infamy is most often used to talk about famously evil or terrible people or historical events. The day the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor, just before the start of World War II, was described by President Roosevelt as \"\"a day that will live in infamy.\"\" Infamy contains the root word \"\"fame,\"\" but rather than meaning \"\"the opposite of famous,\"\" its