d slowly in the days before widespread telegraphy, but by 1849 the Gold Rush was on.</br>3) In its early days, the 1840s­­–1860s, telegraphy had been mythologized as a way to move up in the world.</br>4) It was the nexus where everything — advanced steam technology, mass production, railroads, telegraphy — merged.</br>5) Wireless telegraphy as invented by Guglielmo Marconi, later evolving into radio, set information free from wires.</br>\"\npervasive,\"1) adj spreading or spread throughout</br></br>When something is pervasive, it's everywhere. Common things are pervasive — like greed and cheap perfume.</br></br> Ever notice how certain trends seem to spread all over the place? When something — like a hairstyle — is super-common, it's pervasive. Pervasive things can't be escaped. Playing video games is pervasive among kids. Talking about the weather is pervasive among adults. Ideas, diseases, habits, and all sorts of things can be pervasive. If you're sick of seeing something because you're seeing it again and again, it must be pervasive.</br></br> 1) The pervasive attitude was one of reluctant acceptance.</br>2) \"\"Waste, fraud, abuse, and a pervasive lack of accountability.\"\"</br>3) Football’s world governing body, FIFA, more than any other sports organisation, has become a global symbol of this pervasive corruption.</br>4) When they could not do so, they scrutinized the original data set of individual respondents, called microdata, and found pervasive irregularities.</br>5) The mechanisms to prevent and cope with these crises can only be technological, particularly in the form of environmental engineering, biotechnology, and pervasive computing.</br>\"\nstaunch,\"1) adj firm and dependable especially in loyalty</br>2) v stop the flow of a liquid</br></br>As an adjective, staunch means firm. You might want to go to that concert Friday night, but your parents' staunch opposition prevents you.</br></br> Staunch is sometimes used as a verb to mean \"\"to stop the flow of a liquid,\"\" but most usage books will tell you it's better to use the word stanch for the verb. Think of a soldier stopping and standing still, and you will understand the connection between the two meanings. The adjectival form should make you think of \"\"stand,\"\" as in “stand firm,” or \"\"take a stand.\"\" It comes from the French estanche meaning “watertight” and the Latin stanticare, which is probably from stans for “stand.”</br></br> 1) Most of Uefa’s members will back Ali in Friday’s election though some, including Russia and Spain, will remain staunch backers of the incumbent.</br>2) Most of Uefa’s members will back Ali in Friday’s election, though some, including Russia and Spain, will remain staunch backers of the incumbent.</br>3) The rivalry has no real villain or hero figure; all three are staunch and brave, yet they fight against each other, marshaling huge imaginary armies.</br>4) “I believe in the Lord,” the staunch Catholic said.</br>5) \"\"I believe in the Lord,\"\" the staunch Catholic said.</br>\"\nadvocate,\"1) n a person who pleads for a person, cause, or idea</br>2) n a lawyer who pleads cases in court</br>3) v speak, plead, or argue in favor of</br>4) v push for something</br></br>An advocate (AD-və-kit) is someone who supports a cause, like an advocate for outdoor recess. Advocate (AD-və-kate) is also a verb meaning to speak in favor of, so you can advocate for that outdoor recess by urging your school to play outside!</br></br> As a noun, an advocate is a person who represents another person’s interests, like a lawyer does. In fact, the word comes from the courtroom – it’s from Latin advocare, to “add” a “voice.” To advocate is to add a voice of support to a cause or person. An advocate is anyone who adds that voice by representing another person in court, or by supporting or working toward a particular course of action.</br></br> 1) However, the author of the article is advocating a position, not telling you how to think, much 