iew.</br>\"\ndeleterious,\"1) adj harmful to living things</br></br>If something is deleterious, it does harm or makes things worse. Smoking has obvious deleterious effects on your health, not to mention your social life.</br></br> My parents were worried that their divorce would have a deleterious effect on us kids, but in the end it was less harmful than watching them fight all the time. For most plants, a lack of sunlight has very deleterious consequences, but there are some plants that actually do very well in the dark. It's a wonder, given how well-established the science is, that we continue to do things that are deleterious to the fragile ecosystem. We must be willing to live with the deleterious effects.</br></br> 1) Either way, the result is intense inbreeding and the accumulation of deleterious recessive mutations—a phenomenon known as “inbreeding depression.”</br>2) Everyone serious agrees that high minimum wages will have deleterious and notable effects.</br>3) Some readers were upset that I neglected to mention some of the deleterious effects of caffeine.</br>4) He wrote that the directive “is having such a deleterious effect in this country by effectively outlawing the use of certain herbal extracts.”</br>5) He wrote that the directive \"\"is having such a deleterious effect in this country by effectively outlawing the use of certain herbal extracts.\"\"</br>\"\nself-knowledge,\"1) n an understanding of yourself and your goals and abilities</br></br>  1) Clinging unswervingly to Davina’s point of view, the story leaves Sterling a little adrift, not much more than the instrument of her self-knowledge.</br>2) For the younger Cromwell, self-knowledge—the ability to dispense with masks—was the path to wisdom; now it’s the road to damnation.</br>3) That is why self-knowledge is as important to investment success as market knowledge.</br>4) In addition, conveying self-knowledge was more beneficial than being modest.</br>5) The idea was to increase self-knowledge and autonomy through numbers.</br>\"\nin spite of appearance,\"1) adv in reality</br></br>  1) Hard blows on the table like those of a fist, contrasting with gentle taps, may have this origin, in spite of appearance.</br>\"\ncontrast,\"1) n the opposition or dissimilarity of things that are compared</br>2) n the act of distinguishing by comparing differences</br>3) n a conceptual separation or distinction</br>4) n the perceptual effect of the juxtaposition of very different colors</br>5) n the range of optical density and tone on a photographic negative or print (or the extent to which adjacent areas on a television screen differ in brightness)</br>6) v put in opposition to show or emphasize differences</br>7) v to show differences when compared; be different</br></br>The verb contrast means to show a difference, like photos that reveal how much weight someone lost by contrasting the \"\"before\"\" and \"\"after\"\" shots.</br></br> You probably know contrast in its relation to compare. To contrast something is to look for differences among two or more elements, but compare is to do the opposite, to look for similarities. It's easy to tell the difference if you remember that contrast comes from the Latin root contra, and means \"\"against.\"\" Contrast is also a noun meaning basically the same thing — you might notice the contrast of a dark tree against a snow-covered hill.</br></br> 1) By contrast, the evangelical share of the population decreased, though minimally, from a larger 26.3 percent of the population to 25.4.</br>2) By contrast, not a single one of 25 colorectal patients lacking mutations in mismatch repair genes responded.</br>3) Elliot, by contrast, wants to attack E Corp in a \"\"more subtle, safer way.\"\"</br>4) By contrast, he said, Lebanon had accepted 1.8 million refugees over four years \"\"so today, one in three people in Lebanon is a Syrian refugee.\"\"</br>5) In contrast five out of six workers in the lowest pay grade are ethnic minorities.</br>\"\nconventional,\"1) adj following accepted customs and proprieties</br>2) adj conforming with accepted standards</br>3) adj in accord with or being a tradition or practice accepted from the past</br>4) adj rigidly formal or bound by convention</br>5) adj unimaginative and conformist</br>6) adj represented in simplified or symbolic form</br>7) adj (weapons) using energy for propulsion or destruction that is not nuclear energy</br></br>Conventional is an adjective for things that are normal, ordinary, and following the accepted way. Ho-hum.</br></br> This word describes what is typical and ordinary and that which follows accepted standards of behavior or taste. This is a word that's current definition is still very similar to its Latin root, conventionalis, which is \"\"pertaining to an agreement.\"\" One way this word is used is with respect to conventional weapons, as in those \"\"not using, making, or involving nuclear weapons or energy; nonnuclear.\"\"</br></br> 1) Combined with conventional corn ethanol, the proposed volumes overall rise 9 percent. </br>2) \"\"I tried to record it in a conventional way and it sounded very conventional, it sounded like an average piano,\"\" Frahm said.</br>3) Let them forsake the conventional bromides and put forth radical ideas.</br>4) The Virginia man had undergone dozens of conventional operations to try to repair damage from the shooting accident in 1997, when he was 22.</br>5) Many of the plants grown today by both conventional and organic farmers were created with brute force and imprecise methods, scientists said.</br>\"\nhierarchical,\"1) adj classified according to various criteria into successive levels or layers</br></br>If something is hierarchical it has clear levels of power and importance, such as a hierarchical corporation that has the boss at the top, or the hierarchical social order of junior high school popularity.</br></br> It's lonely at the top. That pretty much sums up hierarchical, pronounced \"\"high-eh-RAR-ki-cal.\"\" In a hierarchical structure, people or groups are arranged according to ability or status. It helps to think of a triangle, with the leader at the highest point, layers of managers under him or her, and at the base, or widest part, the masses of workers who make up the largest part of the organization.</br></br> 1) Shareholder value theory and executive compensation in stock leads to a short-term focus and hierarchical bureaucracy.</br>2) It wasn’t his title — he often swayed colleagues at the same hierarchical level.</br>3) Offices are ranked in a hierarchical order and their operations are characterised by impersonal rules.</br>4) Moving from a very hierarchical and ‘command and control’ environment to the Teal colour is not for the faint of heart.</br>5) At the time, the Harley-Davidson subculture was a relatively homogeneous and hierarchical one, centered on the norms of personal freedom, patriotism, and machismo.</br>\"\nauthoritarian,\"1) adj characteristic of an absolute ruler or absolute rule; having absolute sovereignty</br>2) adj expecting unquestioning obedience</br>3) n a person who behaves in a tyrannical manner</br></br>If your teacher orders you to detention every time you show up to class with a dull pencil, you could probably describe her as an authoritarian — a ruler who prefers order to freedom.</br></br> Authoritarian and authority both begin with author, which comes from an ancient Latin word meaning \"\"master,\"\" \"\"teacher,\"\" or \"\"leader.\"\"    The connection between authoritarian and master is obvious enough, and you can think of an author as the master of the fictional world she creates. Authoritarian is also an adjective.  That teacher with the rule against dull pencils?  You can use the noun form to say that she's an authoritarian, or you can use an adjective and skip the \"\"an\"\": \"\"She's authoritarian.\"\"</br></br> 1) America’s police culture is both authoritarian and racist.</br>2) The news of a high profile Tajik commander joining IS is bound to have shocked Tajikistan's authoritarian government.</br>3) The guards were quick to exert authoritarian control over prisoners, and subject them to physical and extreme psychological torture.</br>4) Instead of the best of all possible worlds, the international community now faces an unholy trinity of authoritarian politics, cutthroat economics, and Big Brother surveillance.</br>5) Extremist movements are opportunistic and value disruptive political change, particularly when it dislodges authoritarian governments that have been their longtime enemies.</br>\"\nmonopoly,\"1) n (economics) a market in which there are many buyers but only one seller</br>2) n exclusive control or possession of something</br></br>A monopoly is the exclusive ownership or control of something. If your sister claims a monopoly over the television during the Tom Cruise movie marathon, you would be wise not to touch that remote.</br></br> In economics, a monopoly specifically means the domination of a market by one owner or seller. Think of the board game Monopoly. You’re trying to own all the properties so that you have a monopoly over the board and the other players have to pay you basically anywhere they land. You might recognize the prefix mono, meaning “one.\"\" Add it to the Greek word polein which means “sell,” and there you have it — one seller.</br></br> 1) The problem with Lord Business isn’t that he runs a company or that he sells products; it’s that he’s a monopoly.</br>2) Before the internet, market power was equated with monopoly, the power of a single seller across a large market.</br>3) The result: “It’s a monopoly situation, and the monopolist takes advantage of that.”</br>4) The skull shows that our species, Homo sapiens, cannot claim a monopoly on murder.</br>5) Precisely...The monopolies that exist in most broadband markets have been strengthened, not weakened, by the 'net neutrality' ruling.</br>\"\npervert,\"1) v corrupt morally or by intemperance or sensuality</br>2) n a person whose behavior deviates from what is acceptable especially in sexual behavior</br>3) v change the inherent purpose or function of something</br>4) v practice sophistry; change the meaning of or be vague about in order to mislead or deceive</br></br>A pervert is a person who doesn't behave normally, often when it comes to sex: perverts pervert the accepted rules of society.</br></br> The most common use of pervert is as a word for people who are deviant sexually: that could mean a lot of things, ranging from being kinky to being dangerous, such as pedophiles. Perverting also means changing or subverting something. A cop who breaks the law is perverting the law. A criminal who convinces other people to become criminals is perverting them. So when you think of pervert, think change — change for the worse.</br></br> 1) A \"\"perverted\"\" man has been jailed for 22 years for abusing a boy he groomed for sex in the 1970s.</br>2) The failure of progressive politics in the Middle East was fuelling \"\"distorted and perverted\"\" interpretations of Islam, she added.</br>3) At 11, he picked up from family conversations that “gays were perverts who practise anal sex.”</br>4) As Schultz notes, Buckley had less to lose than Mailer, whom he had called, two years earlier, in National Review, a “moral pervert.”</br>5) Meanwhile, attempts to make the wealthy pay their fair share have utterly perverted our politics.</br>\"\nprovision,\"1) n the activity of supplying or providing something</br>2) n a store or supply of something (especially of food or clothing or arms)</br>3) n a stipulated condition</br>4) n the cognitive process of thinking about what you will do in the event of something happening</br>5) v supply with provisions</br></br>A provision is a store or supply of something, like food or clothing. This noun can also describe the planning you do for \"\"when something happens.\"\"</br></br> We often use this word when we talk about outdoor activities like hiking or camping, or when we talk about outfitting an army in the field, but it basically means \"\"supply.\"\" And since provision comes from the Latin word that means to \"\"attend to,\"\" you can pretty much guess what the verb form of this word describes: the act of supplying someone else with provisions. In a legal or contractual sense, a provision is a stipulated condition or proviso.</br></br> 1) The Patriot Act provisions for phone data collection are set to expire on Monday, which could lead to a Sunday session of the Senate.</br>2) Senate is planning to work in a rare Sunday session to address the expiring phone-data-collection provisions under the Patriot Act.</br>3) Senate is returning Sunday with just hours to go before a deadline to renew the provisions.</br>4) Surely Congress would have never have written such a risky provision.</br>5) Democrats failed in an effort to attach a currency-manipulation provision to the fast-track bill – an amendment, averting a potential presidential veto.</br>\"\nintegrity,\"1) n an undivided or unbroken completeness or totality with nothing wanting</br>2) n moral soundness</br></br>Integrity is a personal quality of fairness that we all aspire to — unless you're a dishonest, immoral scoundrel, of course.</br></br> Having integrity means doing the right thing in a reliable way. It's a personality trait that we admire, since it means a person has a moral compass that doesn't waver. It literally means having \"\"wholeness\"\" of character, just as an integer is a \"\"whole number\"\" with no fractions. Physical objects can display integrity, too — if you're going over a rickety old bridge that sways in the wind, you might question its structural integrity.</br></br> 1) The integrity of your market is critical, but so is eating and paying the rent.</br>2) He said France was \"\"essentially a decent man of solid integrity.\"\"</br>3) A subsequent report by CONCAF’s integrity committee accused both of fraud and misuse of funds.</br>4) We have no reason to trust the courts as those tasked with sustaining their integrity have done nothing.</br>5) “I stand ready to win this seat back and restore honesty, integrity and competence to the NH-01 seat.”</br>\"\nevangelist,\"1) n a preacher of the Christian gospel</br></br>An evangelist is a preacher, specifically a Christian preacher. Evangelists are excited to tell everyone all over the world about Christianity.</br></br> If you're an evangelist, you're a Christian preacher. Unlike other religious words — such as prayer and God — this word is specifically limited to the Christian faith. With a capital e, Evangelist refers specifically to the authors of the Gospels in the New Testament. Sometimes the word is used more loosely when people say someone is an evangelist for a cause, such as vegetarianism or health care: that means they're a strong believer in and proponent of the cause.</br></br> 1) Esperantists are linguistic evangelists — the community saw an opportunity for expansion, and pounced.</br>2) Mr. Salvi, a former member of the New York Philharmonic who was equal parts harpist, artisan, engineer and evangelist, established the company in 1956.</br>3) Caught up in the waves of technology, I became an evangelist for 3-D technology and medical design.</br>4) Sunday, 10 a.m. to 1:30 p.m.: 30th anniversary worship service, with evangelist Susie C. Owens, co-pastor of Greater Mount Calvary Holy Church in Washington.</br>5) His example is Disney, whose objective is to create advocacy among children who then turn into evangelists 40 years later.</br>\"\nderived,\"1) adj formed or developed from something else; not original</br></br>When something is derived from something else, it is made from that. Ham is derived from pork, and the active ingredient in aspirin is derived from the bark of the willow tree.</br></br> It's best to use derived when you can still see the parts of the original in something. Some