rs should be wary when Charter's Rutledge proclaims that broadband service is about to become better and cheaper.</br>5) The agency has been wary of sending case officers onto the streets in war zones without bodyguards from the paramilitary Global Response Staff.</br>\"\ncity limits,\"1) n the limits of the area occupied by a city or town</br></br>  1) City code prohibits residents from selling or giving away very young fowl, but there are no specific regulations on keeping chickens in the city limits.</br>2) The north Texas city of Denton became a beacon for the anti-fracking movement when residents voted to prohibit the practice inside city limits.</br>3) That’s because all of the low-wage workers who kept their jobs, many of whom live outside the city limits, would get a sizable pay raise.</br>4) He was arrested for investigation of aggravated domestic assault and discharging a firearm within city limits.</br>5) Baltimore police have argued that Gray's knife was illegal inside city limits.</br>\"\npirating,\"1) n someone who robs at sea or plunders the land from the sea without having a commission from any sovereign nation</br>2) n a ship that is manned by pirates</br>3) n someone who uses another person's words or ideas as if they were his own</br>4) v take arbitrarily or by force</br>5) v copy illegally; of published material</br></br>  1) In need of additional computing power and legal protection against the pirating claims, YouTube’s founders decided to sell in 2006.</br>2) But the pirating industry is \"\"built on theft and deception,\"\" according to the report, titled \"\"Good Money Still Going Bad.\"\"</br>3) People running pirated copies of Windows are going to have to pay — or keep pirating — if they want to update their computers to Windows 10.</br>4) The current reimbursement already is big enough that there are 629 charter schools pirating students from neighborhood schools in Texas.</br>5) \"\"Guess pirating copyrighted content is Twitter's new business model,\"\" responded one user.</br>\"\nideology,\"1) n an orientation that characterizes the thinking of a group or nation</br>2) n imaginary or visionary theorization</br></br>An ideology is a set of opinions or beliefs of a group or an individual. Very often ideology refers to a set of political beliefs or a set of ideas that characterize a particular culture.</br></br> Capitalism, communism, socialism, and Marxism are ideologies. But not all -ism words are. Think: cronyism (a system of graft whereby friends unfairly help each other make money.) Our English noun is from French idéologie. The suffix –logy, used with many English words describing theories or doctrines, is from Greek logos \"\"word, reason, speech, account.\"\"</br></br> 1) Also interesting, although we have no recent updates in the Roper Center’s poll archive, are figures about self-described ideology.</br>2) “This amendment is about prioritizing our national security over ideology,” McKinley said, apparently without irony.</br>3) Mr Cotto argues that negotiations with groups that have an ideology or a political vision have been successful.</br>4) Democracy would take a backseat to bureaucracy as technocrats with no particular ideology ran the countries in both blocs in that now-distant two-superpower world.</br>5) Mandatory “diversity training,” in which students are instructed and indoctrinated in an officially-approved ideology, is all too common.</br>\"\nspyware,\"1) n computer software that obtains information from a user's computer without the user's knowledge or consent</br></br>  1) For years, activists and governments alike have been lobbying for more controls on spyware and the research that fuels it.</br>2) Foreign regimes use spyware against journalists, even in U.S.</br>3) The Drug Enforcement Agency has been spending millions on spyware tools to take over suspects' phones, according to an exclusive report from Motherboard.</br>4) Researchers also found computers infected with spyware in the United States, United Kingdom and Canada.  </br>5) Citizen Lab identified the program as a product of Hacking Team - an Italian company that specializes in spyware geared to law enforcement and intelligence agencies.</br>\"\negregious,\"1) adj conspicuously and outrageously bad or reprehensible</br></br>Something that is egregious stands out, but not in a good way — it means \"\"really bad or offensive,\"\" like a tattoo on a man misspelling his girlfriend's name.</br></br> \"\"My massage therapist gave me bruises,\"\" someone complained recently on Twitter, asking, \"\"When does it cease to be deep tissue massage therapy and become egregious and unabashed manhandling?\"\" An egregious error is hardly forgivable. Some synonyms are shocking, appalling, and intolerable. The word has made a 180-degree turn from its original sense in Latin, when it meant \"\"exceptionally good.\"\" Word historians have speculated that the negative usage was originally meant to be ironic, but it is the only sense that has survived. Be careful not to use it to mean \"\"outstanding,\"\" since no one wants to be called egregious.</br></br> 1) Our intrepid team of investigators has diagnosed the most egregious cheaters among us.</br>2) However, no individual has the right to an after-the-fact vengeance killing, no matter how egregious the original act.</br>3) He concludes, calling The Lego Movie an “especially egregious slam on business.”</br>4) Of all of Walmart’s egregious practices overtime, this is the one that’s probably the most well-known.</br>5) This is the only way to make this egregiously expensive healthcare system re-organize itself to  a lower cost base.</br>\"\nvariant,\"1) n something a little different from others of the same type</br>2) n an event that departs from expectations</br>3) n a variable quantity that is random</br>4) n (biology) a group of organisms within a species that differ in trivial ways from similar groups</br>5) adj exhibiting variation and change</br>6) adj differing from a norm or standard</br></br>A variant is another version of something. You could say chimps and apes and gorillas are variants in the primate family.</br></br> Words often have variants, spellings that vary from region to region or country to country. The British colour and the American color are variants. When a movie or TV show is remade or casts a new actor — like with the string of James Bonds — you could call those movies variants. Where there are variants, there is variety — things aren't all the same.</br></br> 1) SIVcpz-infected chimps have a significantly higher frequency of the relatively rare genetic variant that is linked to protection from disease in humans.</br>2) In the first variant, the Chinese side relentlessly introduces new issues as quickly as old ones are resolved, resulting in an endless negotiation.</br>3) The Air Force’s variant is expected to be declared ready for combat sometime late next year.</br>4) But some skeptics argue that the new fossils might be variant individuals of Lucy’s own species.</br>5) But not all gene mutations, or variants, are equal.</br>\"\ncommunism,\"1) n a political theory favoring collectivism in a classless society</br>2) n a form of socialism that abolishes private ownership</br></br>At the opposite end of the spectrum from \"\"capitalism,\"\" communism is an economic theory favoring a classless society and the abolition of private property.</br></br> Communism derives from the French commun (common). Ideally, according to communism, society shares all property in common, everyone shares the burden of labor, and everyone shares the profits of that labor. Or, as the German philosopher Karl Marx wrote, \"\"From each according to his ability, to each according to his need.\"\" As a system of government, communism is often closer to a form of socialism, in which the state owns and operates industry on behalf of the people.</br></br> 1) So sad,  the left has so many wonderful, beautiful 